<div id="review_1343767946" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1343767946" />
    <a title="Kim Kaso" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39507342-kim-kaso"><img alt="Kim Kaso" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1437688314p2/39507342.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1343767946?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kim Kaso" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kim Kaso" href="/user/show/39507342-kim-kaso">Kim Kaso</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143119746" href="/book/show/10042271-the-little-drummer-girl">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39507342-kim-kaso?shelf=5000-books-lor2018">5000-books-lor2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1343767946" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10468584348587263195">I read this book the first time when it first came out, I read it at least two more times before this read, and I‚Äôve watched the movie with Diane Keaton, Klaus Kinski , &amp; the marvelous Sami Frey many times. I did this re-read before watching the recent mini-series, which was well done but felt less romantic than the cinematic version. <br/><br/>I am a huge Le Carr√© fan, I started with <b>The Spy Who Came in from the Cold</b> which was something I read in junior high and came to appreciate in re-reads, but I fell</span>
  <span id="freeText10468584348587263195" style="display:none">I read this book the first time when it first came out, I read it at least two more times before this read, and I‚Äôve watched the movie with Diane Keaton, Klaus Kinski , &amp; the marvelous Sami Frey many times. I did this re-read before watching the recent mini-series, which was well done but felt less romantic than the cinematic version. <br /><br />I am a huge Le Carr√© fan, I started with <b>The Spy Who Came in from the Cold</b> which was something I read in junior high and came to appreciate in re-reads, but I fell hard for George Smiley in <b>Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy</b> and the rest of the Quest for Karla books. (I sometimes feel we are living in the midst of a Le Carr√© series, with more idiotic characters in many cases...). <br /><br />This book was a departure from the Smiley books, and I read it quickly...as quickly as one can a Le Carr√© book as he requires close reading, his writing is exceedingly nuanced, and any hints he gives tend to be limited to a phrase or a quiet sentence. Every time I re-read I discover new subtleties. The scenes where the team breaks Charlie down, pierces her facade, is choreographed beautifully, as is her dual relationship with Joseph/Michel. This book had me on the edge of my seat, Charlie is fascinating as are Kurtz and his team, Joseph is so complex, Khalil is terrifying and yet every character is written with empathy (the preface to my newer edition was a fascinating read in itself as it discussed David Cornwall‚Äôs (Le Carr√©‚Äôs) research, part of which sounded risky in the extreme, and I felt I could see, hear, feel them all. I became emotionally involved with this book in a way that has happened with very few books in my life, and the ending and aftermath leaves me verklempt every time. <br /><br />I read and re-read Le Carr√©, he is a masterful writer who transcends his genre. Very highly recommended, an outstanding read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10468584348587263195" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


