    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_653965013" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/653965013" />
    <a title="Craig" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8691746-craig"><img alt="Craig" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/653965013?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Craig" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Craig" href="/user/show/8691746-craig">Craig</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer653965013" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3190929394917724892">Set in 1970s Western Europe and spots in the Middle-East, this is a relatively fair and well researched fictional depiction of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict with two main characters propelling the narrative. First, there&apos;s Kurtz, an experienced Israeli intelligence agent leading a team of Mossad agents in pursuit of a ghost-like Palestinian terrorist known only as Khalil, whose bombs have left several prominent Jewish targets dead in Western Europe. Secondly, there&apos;s Charlie, a young and aspi</span>
  <span id="freeText3190929394917724892" style="display:none">Set in 1970s Western Europe and spots in the Middle-East, this is a relatively fair and well researched fictional depiction of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict with two main characters propelling the narrative. First, there's Kurtz, an experienced Israeli intelligence agent leading a team of Mossad agents in pursuit of a ghost-like Palestinian terrorist known only as Khalil, whose bombs have left several prominent Jewish targets dead in Western Europe. Secondly, there's Charlie, a young and aspiring British actress whose loudly Leftist politics and pro-Palestinian stance make her the perfect lure for Kurtz and his team to draw out the elusive Khalil. Seduced and beguiled by one of Kurtz's team, Charlie allows herself to be, in Kurtz's words, put into "The Theater of the Real," where her role as the bait for Kahlil may cost her her life. <br /><br />le Carre's detailed prose is always a pleasure to read and his insights into human nature are often poignant and illuminating. In some ways he's like a more real-world version of Gabriel Garcia Marquez in his illustrations of human nature. Even the more sinister personalities in his books are given a non-judgmental depiction that, however repulsive they might otherwise be, make them understandable and saves them from merely being something to despise. And by doing so, le Carre illustrates quite well how complicated such issues as the Israeli-Palestinian conflict (among countless others) are. Khalil is a monster, but his violent acts, while not justified, are given some context that lets his humanity, however damaged, show through. Granted, there is judgement in this book; you'll never doubt who to root for, but le Carre makes the enemy flesh and blood, instead of merely an abstract monster for whom elimination is their only reason for existing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3190929394917724892" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

